    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1971-12-10T10:39:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1971-12-10T10:39:00-05:00" n="264"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d264">
                <head>264. Telegram From <gloss type="from">the Department of State</gloss> to
                        <gloss type="to">the Embassy in Pakistan</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d264fn1">Source: National Archives, RG 59,
                        Central Files 1970–73, <gloss target="#t_POL1">POL</gloss> 27 INDIA–<gloss
                            target="#t_PAK1">PAK</gloss>. Secret; Flash. Drafted by <persName
                            corresp="#p_SJJ1">Sisco</persName> and approved by <persName
                            corresp="#p_JUA1">U. Alexis Johnson</persName>. Repeated to New Delhi,
                        Dacca, and <gloss target="#t_USUN1">USUN</gloss>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1971-12-10T15:39:00+00:00">December 10, 1971,
                        1539Z</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>222703. Islamabad for Ambassador.</p>
                <p>You will have seen Dacca 5573.<note n="2" xml:id="d264fn2">See <ref
                            target="#d263fn3">footnote 3, Document 263</ref>.</note> Contact
                        <persName corresp="#p_YKA1">Yahya</persName> immediately. Confirm whether
                    this is the bona fide Pak position. If so ask him whether he would like us to be
                    helpful vis-à-vis the <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> with communications and
                    otherwise.</p>
                <p>Does this mean that <persName corresp="#p_YKA1">Yahya</persName> is ready for a
                    cease-fire in the West? If he is, we want him to know that we are ready to make
                    a major effort <pb facs="0769" n="740" xml:id="pg_740"/> to bring it about in
                    order to preserve Pakistan territorial integrity and armed forces.</p>
                <p>Please respond flash.<note n="3" xml:id="d264fn3">Ambassador <persName
                            corresp="#p_FJS1">Farland</persName> contacted Foreign Secretary
                            <persName corresp="#p_SKM1">Sultan Khan</persName> who consulted with
                        President <persName corresp="#p_YKA1">Yahya</persName> and confirmed
                        Pakistanʼs request for a <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss>-organized
                        cease-fire in East Pakistan. <persName corresp="#p_SKM1">Sultan
                            Khan</persName> said that Pakistan was also ready for a <gloss
                            target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss>-monitored cease-fire in the west, to be
                        followed by negotiations to effect a troop withdrawal and a settlement of
                        the war. (Telegram 12355 from Islamabad, December 10; National Archives, RG
                        59, Central Files 1970–73, <gloss target="#t_POL1">POL</gloss> 27
                            INDIA–<gloss target="#t_PAK1">PAK</gloss>)</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="strong">Irwin</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
